 =20
  <div>
    <h2 id=3D"8611441451a6" class=3D"text-2xl font-bold mb-3 mt-5 p-1 bg-gr=
ay-100 font-raleway overflow-hidden">
     =20
        <a class=3D"inline-block" href=3D"https://docs.vectric.com/docs/V12=
.0/VCarvePro/ENU/Help/form/post-processor-editing/#8611441451a6">
          <img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://docs.vectric.com/docs/V12.0/=
VCarvePro/shared/icons/link.svg">
        </a>
     =20
      Special Characters
    </h2>
    <div><p class=3D"mt-3">Most characters can be output within the confine=
s of the post processor output statements; however, certain characters have=
 special meaning within the post processor configuration files and cannot b=
e output directly.</p><p class=3D"mt-3">These are, the Square brackets [ ],=
 and the double quote character =E2=80=9C It may be the case that you need =
to output one of these characters within your output file.</p><p class=3D"m=
t-3">If you wish to output one of these characters, you can do so by enclos=
ing the decimal equivalent of the ASCII value of the special character that=
 you wish to output, within square brackets, as shown below. This method ca=
n also be used to insert any ASCII value, even non-printable characters.</p=
><ul><li>[91] Outputs a left hand square bracket.</li><li>[93] Outputs a ri=
ght hand square bracket.</li><li>[34] Outputs a double quote character.</li=
><li>[13] Outputs a carriage return.</li><li>[10] Outputs a line feed.</li>=
</ul><p class=3D"mt-3"><em>For an example of a file that uses special chara=
cters, please see: Biesse_Rover_Arcs_mm.pp</em></p></div>
  </div>
 =20

     =20

     =20
   =20

     =20
       =20
 =20
    <div>
      <h2 id=3D"ed08d7dc9775" class=3D"text-2xl font-bold mb-3 mt-5 p-1 bg-=
gray-100 font-raleway overflow-hidden">
       =20
          <a class=3D"inline-block" href=3D"https://docs.vectric.com/docs/V=
12.0/VCarvePro/ENU/Help/form/post-processor-editing/#ed08d7dc9775">
            <img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://docs.vectric.com/docs/V12.=
0/VCarvePro/shared/icons/link.svg">
          </a>
       =20
        Example: Adding Tool-Change Commands
      </h2>
      <div><p class=3D"mt-3">For the majority of cases, the quickest and ea=
siest way of producing a customised post processor to suit your controller,=
 will be to edit an existing post processor. To do this, first create a sim=
ple test file that you can use to test the output of your post processor. A=
 simple file might consist of a line, and two circles. Produce a shallow cu=
tting profile toolpaths for each of the shapes, machining =E2=80=9COn=E2=80=
=9D the line, =E2=80=9CInside=E2=80=9D one of the circles and =E2=80=9COuts=
ide=E2=80=9D the other circle.</p><p class=3D"mt-3"></p><div><div class=3D"=
flex flex-row justify-center items-baseline flex-wrap"><div class=3D"flex f=
lex-col items-center"><img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://cdn.sanity.io/im=
ages/i7cqi3ri/12/20a872b7fc0d22f087418e981e6722da48aa5862-1915x971.png" cla=
ss=3D"m-2" style=3D"max-width:300px;"></div></div></div><p class=3D"mt-3">S=
ave a toolpath using your base post processor and take a look at it using y=
our favourite text editor. Below is an example of the test file posted usin=
g the "G-Code Arcs (inch) (*.tap)" post processor The example below is disp=
layed using the popular Notepad ++ editor.</p><div><div class=3D"flex flex-=
row justify-center items-baseline flex-wrap"><div class=3D"flex flex-col it=
ems-center"><img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://cdn.sanity.io/images/i7cqi=
3ri/12/09891cd21d1243a82ac5f4ec472bcdcf6052929c-742x931.png" class=3D"m-2" =
style=3D"max-width:300px;"></div></div></div><p class=3D"mt-3">For our exam=
ple, we will add a tool-change section to this post processor. Go to the Ma=
chine Configuration option under the machine menu.<br><br>In the Associated=
 Post Processor section, click on the (+) icon and scroll down the list to =
locate your Post Processor in the list.<br>Right click on it and select <st=
rong>Customise</strong><br>A new copy of the Post Processor will appear at =
the top of the list with a pen icon next to it.<br><br>Right click on this =
copy and select <strong>Open File Location</strong><br><br>This will open t=
he Windows folder with the .pp Post Processor file itself which you can the=
n directly edit if you need to adjust commands to fit your particular machi=
ne setup. These .pp Post Processor files can be edited in any standard Text=
 Editor software</p><div><div class=3D"flex flex-row justify-center items-b=
aseline flex-wrap"><div class=3D"flex flex-col items-center"><img loading=
=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://cdn.sanity.io/images/i7cqi3ri/12/983bb7afddc065915=
162604ac1f649ec184305f9-1545x934.png" class=3D"m-2" style=3D"max-width:300p=
x;"></div></div></div><p class=3D"mt-3">To add a Tool Change section to the=
 post processor, you will need to consult the documentation for the control=
 of the machine tool (or control software). For this example, we will assum=
e that the instructions that you need to add to perform a tool change for y=
our particular machine tool are as follows:</p><ul><li>M05 Instruction to t=
urn off the spindle prior to tool change.</li><li>M0 Instruction to return =
existing tool to tool holder.</li><li>M06TTool_Number n Instruction to sele=
ct new tool Tool_Number n</li><li>G43HTool_Number n Instruction for control=
 to use Tool length offset for tool n</li><li>Sxxx M03 Set spindle speed to=
 xxx; Turn on spindle (clockwise rotation).</li></ul></div>
     =20
        <h3 id=3D"5f9509b4c725" class=3D"text-xl font-semibold p-2 mb-2 mt-=
6 font-bold font-raleway overflow-hidden">
         =20
            <a class=3D"inline-block" href=3D"https://docs.vectric.com/docs=
/V12.0/VCarvePro/ENU/Help/form/post-processor-editing/#5f9509b4c725">
              <img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://docs.vectric.com/docs/V1=
2.0/VCarvePro/shared/icons/link.svg">
            </a>
         =20
          Edit the post processor using your favourite text editor.
        </h3>
        <div><p class=3D"mt-3">If the operating system on your computer is =
Microsoft Vista and User Access Control is enabled, copy or move the Post P=
rocessor that you are editing from the PostP folder to a folder below your =
user area.</p><p class=3D"mt-3">The first thing that you should edit within=
 the file is the History Comment section; So that you have a record of the =
changes.</p><div><div class=3D"flex flex-row justify-center items-baseline =
flex-wrap"><div class=3D"flex flex-col items-center"><img loading=3D"lazy" =
src=3D"https://cdn.sanity.io/images/i7cqi3ri/12/0c7259aef34b56a1aa77573e522=
dc9e4f2c83dbc-693x464.png" class=3D"m-2" style=3D"max-width:300px;"></div><=
/div></div><p class=3D"mt-3">Next edit the POST_NAME to reflect that this p=
ost processor outputs automatic tool change (ATC) commands, the new post wi=
ll be displayed as =E2=80=9CG-Code ATC Arcs (inch)(*.tap)=E2=80=9D in the l=
ist of post processors.</p><div><div class=3D"flex flex-row justify-center =
items-baseline flex-wrap"><div class=3D"flex flex-col items-center"><img lo=
ading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://cdn.sanity.io/images/i7cqi3ri/12/a75e8eba2ec2=
520c47ee96026c4bc360c7cd1a81-693x518.png" class=3D"m-2" style=3D"max-width:=
300px;"></div></div></div><p class=3D"mt-3">Next add a Tool Change Section =
that will include the instructions. The location of the new section within =
the file is not important, but a good place to insert it is between the Hea=
der and Rapid Move sections.</p><div><div class=3D"flex flex-row justify-ce=
nter items-baseline flex-wrap"><div class=3D"flex flex-col items-center"><i=
mg loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://cdn.sanity.io/images/i7cqi3ri/12/40d8c3f=
ed34f26b6e4d923073b8b9de778b61c09-693x504.png" class=3D"m-2" style=3D"max-w=
idth:300px;"></div></div></div><p class=3D"mt-3">Add some comment lines at =
the top of the new section, (beginning with the + character) to describe th=
e section and make the file as a whole, easier to read. Next enter the line=
 =E2=80=9Cbegin TOOLCHANGE=E2=80=9D to instruct the post processor that the=
 following instructions are to be output for every tool-change, (except the=
 initial tool selection, the commands for these are contained within the he=
ader section).</p><p class=3D"mt-3">The next step is to enter in the instru=
ctions that you require, enclosed within double quote marks. The =E2=80=9C[=
T]=E2=80=9D on the third and fourth instruction lines of our example, will =
be substituted with the tool number when the file is post processed; The =
=E2=80=9C[S]=E2=80=9D on the fifth line will be substituted with the spindl=
e speed for the tool.</p><p class=3D"mt-3">Finally you will need to save th=
e changes to the file, as you have changed the POST_NAME, save the file usi=
ng a new name, for example =E2=80=9CGCODE_ATC_Arcs_inch.pp=E2=80=9D</p><p c=
lass=3D"mt-3"><em>If the operating system on your computer is Microsoft Win=
dows 7 or Microsoft Vista and User Access Control is enabled, copy the file=
 that you have edited back to the =E2=80=9CPostP=E2=80=9D folder.</em></p><=
p class=3D"mt-3">To test the new post processor, If the software is running=
, restart the software.</p><p class=3D"mt-3">If there are any syntax errors=
 with your post processor, an error similar to the picture below will be di=
splayed as the software starts, the post processor that you have edited wil=
l not appear in the drop down list of post processor configuration files. Y=
ou will need to rectify any errors and restart the software.</p><div><div c=
lass=3D"flex flex-row justify-center items-baseline flex-wrap"><div class=
=3D"flex flex-col items-center"><img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://cdn.sa=
nity.io/images/i7cqi3ri/12/46842821585af26f47ad3449f31cdb34dfee2b99-443x166=
.png" class=3D"m-2" style=3D"max-width:300px;"></div></div></div><p class=
=3D"mt-3">If there are no errors displayed when the software is started, op=
en your test file and save one or more of your test toolpaths.</p><p class=
=3D"mt-3">Select the post processor from the drop down list of post process=
or configuration and press the =E2=80=9CSave Toolpath(s)=E2=80=9D button.</=
p><p class=3D"mt-3">Take a look at the file that you have just saved in a t=
ext editor.</p><p class=3D"mt-3">If the content of the file looks good, try=
 the file on your machine.</p><p class=3D"mt-3"><strong>Please take all nec=
essary precautions when running the output from a modified post processor f=
or the first time.</strong></p></div>
     =20
    </div>
